Your mirror looks good.

The important proof is:

oc adm release info \
  --image-for=machine-os-images \
  $OPENSHIFT_INSTALL_RELEASE_IMAGE_OVERRIDE

returned:

quay.io/openshift-release-dev/ocp-v4.0-art-dev@sha256:30a4c9...

That means the release payload contains the machine-os-images reference and the installer knows where to get the RHCOS content.

Now run:

OPENSHIFT_INSTALL_RELEASE_IMAGE_OVERRIDE=bastion-sno.lab.ocp.lan:8443/ocp4/openshift4/openshift/release-images:4.20.21-x86_64 \
openshift-install agent create image --dir clusterconfigs --log-level=debug

If it still stops at:

INFO Extracting base ISO from release payload

then check whether the installer can actually pull the machine-os image through the mirror mapping:

oc image info \
bastion-sno.lab.ocp.lan:8443/ocp4/openshift4/openshift/release-images@sha256:54c81ab130a264829c9a3434df1005074cc9b2edc8e31ead40ac94faf3debf72

Also verify:

podman login bastion-sno.lab.ocp.lan:8443

and that your registry CA is trusted:

curl -vk https://bastion-sno.lab.ocp.lan:8443/v2/

One thing I notice: --image-for=machine-os-images returned the original source reference (quay.io/...@sha256) rather than the mirror location. That's normal output from oc adm release info, but during ISO creation the installer must resolve that digest through your ImageDigestSources.

So the next test I'd run is:

OPENSHIFT_INSTALL_RELEASE_IMAGE_OVERRIDE=bastion-sno.lab.ocp.lan:8443/ocp4/openshift4/openshift/release-images:4.20.21-x86_64 \
openshift-install agent create image --dir clusterconfigs --log-level=debug

and capture the lines immediately after:

INFO Extracting base ISO from release payload

Those next 10–20 lines will tell us whether the failure is:

registry authentication,

certificate trust,

digest mirror resolution,

or inability to pull machine-os-images.


From what you've shown so far, the release image itself is present and valid in the mirror.
